    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Echinus cordatum</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_1775",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Test oval, white, very thin and fragile and with a marked anterior notch that extends into a distinct trough that runs to centre of upper side (hence the heart shape). Dorsal ‘petals’ wide and distinctly sunken. Mouth displaced towards anterior end and with a scoop-like posterior lip. Underside bears patches of large tubercles (to which spines attach) separated by smooth channels (where tubefeet emerge). Anus high on posterior end, which is raised and truncated</p><p>Living animal brownish with white spines of more or less uniform length, those on ventral surface with distinctly flattened spoon-like tips (spatulate).</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_1776",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Test diameter up to about 90 mm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_1777",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Widespread from northern Norway along European coast to&nbsp; Mediterranean and Morocco, South Africa, Japan, New Zealand and Southern Australia.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Saldanha Bay to Sodwana Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_1778",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Found buried in clean sand at a depth of about 10-15 cm below the sand surface. Creates a mucus-lined respiratory channel down to the anterior end and this leaves a conical depression at the surface within which detrital material collects, thus revealing the location of the urchin. In Europe lifespan is thought to be about 10 years.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_1779",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Feeds on organic debris in the sand, which it sorts from the sand particles using elongated tubefeet at the anterior end.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_1780",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Sexes are separate and sperm and eggs are released into the water where they merge and form pelagic larvae. In European populations larvae have a duration of about 39 days.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_1781",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Replaced in deeper waters by the similar but smaller (50 mm) <i>E. capense</i>, which also has shorter spines and is deep purple when alive.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_1782",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2022). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fifth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 236).<br><br>Filander, Z & Griffiths, C (2017). Illustrated guide to the echinoid (Echinodermata: Echinoidea) fauna of South Africa. <i>Zootaxa</i>, 4296(1), 1-72. (p. 60)<br><br>Clark, AM & Courtman-Stock, J (1976). The Echinoderms of Southern Africa. British Museum (Natural History), London (p. 251).<br><br>Schultz, H (2010). Sea Urchins 1: A guide to worldwide shallow water species. Heinke and Peter Schultz Partner Scientific Publications. Hemdingen, Germany (p. 411).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_1783",
